ting their confessions,\ncontending they were coerced\nInto signing them after 37\nhours of questioning. Their\nstatements had Implicated Mar\nshall.\n\u201cThey both refused to tes\ntify against Marshall,\" Mr.\nDely declared\ni Marshall was arrested after\ndetectives heard that his\nbrother Archie, 42. had died.\nDetective Bgts. Robert Reed\nand Shirley O\u2019Neill followed the\nfuneral cortege to the Lincoln\nMemorial Cemetery, where they\njoined the mourners at the\ngrave. After the rites were\nover they errrsted Solomon\nMarshall outside the cemetery.\nHe told them he hed been liv\ning in Newark. N. J.. and had\nreturned only for the funeral.\nCongress Triples\nl?se of Library's\nReference Books\nCongress has become more\ninquisitive than ever, Its librar\nian finds.\nThe Nation\u2019s legislators put\nmore than 102.000 Inquiries\nto the Library of Congress dur\ning fiscal 1957, Librarian L.\nQuincy Muuiford said in hie>\n1 annual report.\nThe Library had plenty of\nI resources for the answers.\nwith its collections totaling\ni more than 36 million items\nranging from the latest news\npaper to a Japanese sutra or\nBuddhist prayer printed in\n770 AD.\nAs a matter of fuct, members\nand committee* of Congress\nI have nearly tripled their use\n.of the Library's Legislative\nReference Bervice in the last\n10 years.\nOther Library departments\nhandled nearly double the\nnumber of congressional ques\ntions they recorded in 1947.\nTwo of the Library's opera\ntions set new records again in\nearned revenue.\nThe Library sells to other li\nbraries and to individuals its\nprinted catalog cards. Last\nyear, It sold more than 26 mil\nlion for an all-time high, as\nwell as copies of Its book cata\nlogs and technical library pub\nlications. These sales enabled\nthe Library to put 81.440.999 In\nthe Treasury, or 97 per cent of\nthe appropriation for the\nservice.\nRevenues from registration\nof copyright claims were the\nlargest In the Copyright Office's\nhistory. It turned 6890,019 in\nto the Treasury. A total of\n225.807 books, oerlodtcals. mu\nsic and otter works were reg\nistered for copyright.\nTHE EVENING STAR, Washington, D C.\nWEDNEsnAV. JSNL'ARV INS\nFort Myet Flight\nMarker Sought\nA marker at Fort Myer, Va.,\ncommemorating the first air\nplane flight at an Army in\nstallation would be erected un\nder terms of a bill approved\ni yesterday by the Armed Serv\nices Committee.\nA plaque with the marker\nI would note the first plane\ni crash at an Army installation.\nThe House approved bill\nsets a maximum cost of 83.500\nfor the marker to honor the\ni airplane flight on September\n3, 1908, when Wilbur and Or\ni vllle Wright demonstrated their\ni craft for the Army. The plaque\nwould be In m\u00bbmory of the\ncrash In which L\u00bb Thomas E\nSelfrldge was killed on Sep\ntember 17. 1908.\nRecession is Fading\nPublisher Contends\nThe recession la fading and\nbusiness promises to get better\nand better, an optimistic mag\nazine publisher said here yes\nterday.\nArthur H Motley, publisher\nof Parade, a weekly magazine,\ntold the Board of Trade an\nnual business outlook confer\nence:\n\"Just as the peak of the\nboom passed two years ago,\nthe bottom of whatever it is\nwe're in may be behind, not\nahead of us. The business year\n57-\u2019SB may not be a replica\nof '53-'54. but I suspect it is\n\"A vear from now well all\nbe fighting inflation instead of\nrecession.\"\nA-9","height":"28823","width":"18186"}}
